# **Designing Visual Systems for Automated Brand-Consistent Image Generation**

### Generating single AI images is easy. Creating an AI-powered engine for consistent, brand-aligned visuals is a different story.

[Alena Gorb](https://substack.com/@savvysloth)  
Jan 23, 2026  
![A cartoon sloth with glasses sits on a branch using a laptop. A thought bubble shows 3 organised visual systems being transformed into a Google Sheet table.][image1]

Here we are with Part 2 of my automated visual system testing series. In [Part 1](https://savvysloth.substack.com/p/how-and-why-im-automating-visual), I laid out the *why* and the *how* behind this project, including my tool stack, so go check that out if you haven‚Äôt already.

To recap, the main goal for this project is to build a system that can automatically generate brand-consistent images for Pinterest (or other platform of your choosing) and help you identify which visual system performs best based on user preferences.

This week, we will go over the logic and prompts for two scenarios:

* When you don‚Äôt yet have brand visuals or a clearly defined visual system  
* When you already have brand visuals but want to test and refine them based on user response

Without further ado, pull up a branch, get comfy, and let‚Äôs get prompting\!

#### **The Challenge: Brand-Consistent Image Generation with AI**

Building a brand is more than just creating a collection of random, pretty images. Your brand visuals tell a story and help people form a mental connection between what they see, how it makes them feel, and what you offer.

Think Nike. A simple, white tick logo paired with the catchy ‚ÄúJust do it‚Äù, promoting actions and moving forward. It makes sense that Nike‚Äôs visuals consistently show people in motion, engaging in sports and physical activity.

No flashy effects or over-the-top backgrounds. Just people in sportswear getting on with it. It‚Äôs simple, powerful, and most importantly, consistent and instantly recognisable.

Nike spent years and millions of dollars getting there. With AI, you do not need to wait that long or spend nearly as much to reach a solid (if not quite Nike-level) degree of brand recognition.

That said, AI-generated images introduce a different challenge: reproducibility. You can give the same prompt to the same model and get different results across runs, with even more variation across models.

So when I talk about building a *visual system*, I don‚Äôt just mean a set of image prompts with similar instructions in them. I mean a set of instructions, akin to the brand guidelines, that describe the system clearly enough for both AI models and humans to follow.

For our purposes, an AI-friendly visual system should be:

* **Clear & concrete:** no vague descriptions or abstract vibes  
* **Enforceable:** instructions must be followed precisely within the system constraints  
* **Internally consistent:** key features must appear in every visual  
* **Executable by a machine:** clear input and output requirements tailored to the model

These criteria make the system compatible with automation, but they do not automatically guarantee personality, creativity, or recognisability. To address that, I‚Äôve implemented two features in this project:

1. Application of the SUCCESS framework to anchor each system in 3 dominant dimensions and improve recognisability  
2. Human input & oversight throughout the process

That second one is especially important. Early on, I considered making the workflow essentially hands-free, with hardcoded instructions that would automatically generate 3 visual systems and 30 prompts per system.

But during some pilot testing of the prompts, I realised that I didn‚Äôt always like what the AI output on the first few tries. These weren‚Äôt usually fundamental issues, which could be fixed with clearer prompts; these were more nuanced stylistic preferences that were hard to put into machine-executable format.

Rather than trying to over-engineer the system, I left the final creative decisions to the humans.

There was also a practical constraint: cost. In n8n, I needed an API access to use the commercial cloud-based models. But with many providers (like Google, Anthropic, and OpenAI) tightening their free tier usage, it was cheaper (or free, to be precise) to do a bit of manual copying and pasting between a chatbot and Google Sheets.

Now that we have defined the problem and the constraints, let‚Äôs go through the actual prompts I used for this experiment.

#### **Using These Prompts: Expectations & Flexibility**

Before we dive in, a quick disclaimer and the reasons I don‚Äôt often share my prompts publicly.

I believe that there is no such thing as a ‚Äúperfect prompt‚Äù (although there are certainly bad ones\!) The prompts below are the ones I have tested and found to be ‚Äúgood enough‚Äù for my purposes, with the quality of results differing depending on the model I used (GPT-5.2, Sonnet 4.5, Gemini 3 Thinking).

Treat these as a starting point, not a final destination. Try them as-is and see what you get with your model of choice. If you don‚Äôt like the outputs, add follow-up instructions, or adjust 1 or 2 key parameters and try again. Tinker a little until you‚Äôre 80-90% there, but don‚Äôt overengineer the prompts. We want the outputs to be reproducible rather than a one-shot wonder with the results.

#### **Scenario 1: Creating Visual Systems from Scratch**

This prompt is suitable for anyone early in their visual branding journey, or for those who have a rough idea of what they want but struggle to express it in an AI-friendly way.

Here‚Äôs the visual system design starter prompt:

You are a brand-aware visual systems designer and creative director.

Your task is to design EXACTLY 3 distinct, testable visual systems for AI-generated images that can be used consistently across social media (Instagram, Pinterest, blog visuals, or print-on-demand).

These systems must be:

\- internally consistent  
\- easy to reproduce with AI image models  
\- clearly differentiated from each other  
\- clearly independent from each other (each system can be used in isolation)  
\- suitable for automation and batch generation

Each system must be capable of supporting AT LEAST 30 visually distinct images without changing its core rules.

SUCCESS FRAMEWORK

For EACH system, select a DIFFERENT combination of 3 dominant SUCCESS dimensions. For each selected dimension, explain how it is expressed VISUALLY through enforceable rules (not abstract concepts):

\- Simple  
\- Unexpected  
\- Concrete  
\- Credible  
\- Emotional  
\- Stories

INPUT CONTEXT

1\. Brand name (optional):  
\[leave blank if none\]

2\. Content theme:  
\[e.g. AI workflows, automation, productivity, education\]

3\. Target audience:  
\[who this is for and how they generally think\]

4\. Primary platform(s):  
\[Instagram, Pinterest, blog, print, or combination\]

5\. Emotional tone preferences (optional):  
\[e.g. calm, curious, bold, minimal\]

6\. Visual style preferences (optional):  
\[e.g. illustration, photography, pastel, high contrast\]

7\. Reference aesthetics or creators (optional):  
\[vague or concrete\]

8\. Additional requirements (optional):  
\[any branding guidelines that the system must follow, if available\]

OUTPUT REQUIREMENTS

Return EXACTLY 3 visual systems.

Each system must be formatted using the following STRICT STRUCTURE and LABELS  
(do not merge sections, do not rename labels):

SYSTEM

System ID:  
‚Äì short, unique identifier (e.g. MIN-01, ILL-01, BOLD-01)

System Name:  
‚Äì short, descriptive

Success Dimensions:  
‚Äì list exactly 3, comma-separated (e.g. Simple, Concrete, Credible)

Success Dimensions (Visual Expression):  
‚Äì bullet points explaining how EACH selected dimension is enforced visually

Design Intent:  
‚Äì 1‚Äì2 sentences describing the emotional and strategic signal

Colour Logic:  
‚Äì rules only (no hex codes)

Composition Rules:  
‚Äì layout, spacing, focal hierarchy rules

Typography Style:  
‚Äì descriptive (no font names)

Visual Style:  
‚Äì illustration/photography/texture/realism rules

Prompt Constraints:  
‚Äì explicit MUST/MUST NOT rules for image generation  
‚Äì include subject matter boundaries if relevant

Prompt Instruction:  
‚Äì a SINGLE imperative instruction that tells another AI how to generate final, model-ready image prompts using this system  
‚Äì this instruction should NOT describe the system again  
‚Äì any consistent image element (e.g., recurring image of a sloth) MUST be described in enough detail to reproduce that element consistently, even in the absence of a reference image  
‚Äì it should tell the AI HOW to generate prompts while obeying the system rules

Best Use Cases:  
‚Äì types of posts this system works best for

Risk & Failure Modes:  
‚Äì how this system could drift, become generic, or fail at scale

SYSTEM CONSTRAINTS

\- Avoid trendy buzzwords unless necessary  
\- Prioritise clarity and repeatability over novelty  
\- Assume images will be generated at scale via automation  
\- Do NOT optimise for virality clich√©s

If no brand name is provided:

\- infer a neutral but distinctive starting point based on the inputs  
\- state assumptions briefly at the top before the systems

The prompt should be fairly self-explanatory, but there are a few things worth calling out.

Right off the bat, this is a long prompt. But there are two key reasons for it:

* I added additional spacing purely to make it easier to read (you‚Äôre welcome üòÑ).  
* The prompt is designed to be model-agnostic. While more advanced models are good at giving the desired outputs with much less prompting, much smaller local models work better if you tell them *exactly* what you‚Äôre after.

Secondly, the system requirements of ‚Äúclearly differentiated‚Äù and ‚Äúclearly independent‚Äù are important. Differentiation ensures that you‚Äôre not just testing variations on the same theme; you‚Äôre testing different visual approaches.

System independence matters because, in early iterations of this prompt, AI kept creating systems designed to work together. It might be exactly what you want, but for my project, I wanted each system to be complete in isolation. But you do you, boo booüòò\!

I also included the instructions on how each system needs to dominate different combinations of SUCCESS dimensions. You don‚Äôt need to use SUCCESS specifically; any other framework with clear parameters should work, or you can remove this part altogether.

But if you end up including a framework, make sure to ask the model to explain how the parameters are ‚Äúexpressed visually through enforceable rules.‚Äù That makes the framework part of the system rather than decorative commentary.

The last part of the prompt, when the brand name is not provided, is interesting. Most of the input fields are optional, so the less you fill in, the more the model will have to ‚Äúguess‚Äù based on its training and, where available, its memory of your preferences. Asking it to state assumptions makes that reasoning visible.

#### **My Test Case: Savvy Sloth Inputs**

For Savvy Sloth, I used the following inputs:

---

1. **Brand name (if any):** Savvy Sloth  
2. **Content Theme:** Experimenting and testing AI workflows and automations  
3. **Target audience:** Working professionals who want to learn about and use automations and AI enthusiasts  
4. **Primary platform(s):** Pinterest  
5. **Emotional tone preferences (optional):** Calm but still playful, credible but still light-hearted, slightly ironic and quietly contrarian  
6. **Visual style preferences (optional):** Beige and other pastel colours, no sharp edges or aggressive contrast, maybe cartoony  
7. **Reference aesthetics or creators (optional):** Apple and Hugging Face branding  
8. **Additional requirements (optional):** N/A  
---

#### **Scenario 2: Creating Visual Systems from Reference Images**

This approach is for cases where you already have one or a few brand images you like, but don‚Äôt yet have a formal system that an AI model can follow.

The prompt is largely based on the previous one, but instead of describing preferences verbally, we will show AI a reference image and ask it to reverse-engineer the underlying system.

So here‚Äôs the visual system design from the reference image prompt:

You are a brand-aware visual systems designer and creative director.

Your task is to use the reference image attached to reverse-engineer the visual brand system for me.

The system must be:

\- internally consistent  
\- easy to reproduce with AI image models  
\- suitable for automation and batch generation

The system must be capable of supporting AT LEAST 30 visually distinct images without changing its core rules.

SUCCESS FRAMEWORK

For the system, select 3 dominant SUCCESS dimensions. For each selected dimension, explain how it is expressed VISUALLY through enforceable rules (not abstract concepts):

\- Simple  
\- Unexpected  
\- Concrete  
\- Credible  
\- Emotional  
\- Stories

INPUT CONTEXT

1\. Reference image (required):  
\[1-3 images to be used to create a verbal description of the visual system\]

2\. Brand name (optional):  
\[leave blank if none\]

3\. Content theme (optional):  
\[e.g. AI workflows, automation, productivity, education\]

4\. Target audience (optional):  
\[who this is for and how they generally think\]

5\. Primary platform(s):   
\[Instagram, Pinterest, blog, print, or combination\]

6\. Additional requirements (optional):  
\[any branding guidelines that the system must follow\]

OUTPUT REQUIREMENTS

Return EXACTLY 1 visual system.

The system must be formatted using the following STRICT STRUCTURE and LABELS  
(do not merge sections, do not rename labels):

SYSTEM

System ID:  
‚Äì short, unique identifier (e.g. MIN-01, ILL-01, BOLD-01)

System Name:  
‚Äì short, descriptive

Success Dimensions:  
‚Äì list exactly 3, comma-separated (e.g. Simple, Concrete, Credible)

Success Dimensions (Visual Expression):  
‚Äì bullet points explaining how EACH selected dimension is enforced visually

Design Intent:  
‚Äì 1‚Äì2 sentences describing the emotional and strategic signal

Colour Logic:  
‚Äì rules only (no hex codes)

Composition Rules:  
‚Äì layout, spacing, focal hierarchy rules

Typography Style:  
‚Äì descriptive (no font names)

Visual Style:  
‚Äì illustration/photography/texture/realism rules

Prompt Constraints:  
‚Äì explicit MUST/MUST NOT rules for image generation  
‚Äì include subject matter boundaries if relevant

Prompt Instruction:  
‚Äì a SINGLE imperative instruction that tells another AI how to generate final, model-ready image prompts using this system  
‚Äì this instruction should NOT describe the system again  
‚Äì any consistent image element (e.g., recurring image of a sloth) MUST be described in enough detail to reproduce that element consistently, even in the absence of a reference image    
‚Äì it should tell the AI HOW to generate prompts while obeying the system rules

Best Use Cases:  
‚Äì types of posts this system works best for

Risk & Failure Modes:  
‚Äì how this system could drift, become generic, or fail at scale

SYSTEM CONSTRAINTS

\- Avoid trendy buzzwords unless necessary  
\- Prioritise clarity and repeatability over novelty  
\- Assume images will be generated at scale via automation  
\- Do NOT optimise for virality clich√©s

One key difference with this prompt is that it generates only one visual system at a time. I wouldn‚Äôt recommend attaching multiple images for different visual systems at the same time. If you want 3 systems, just use this prompt 3 times in 3 separate chats. Trust me, it'll save you from some visual disasters ‚Ä¶

Below is my example input using the Savvy Sloth logo as a reference image:

1. **Reference image (required):** \[1-3 images to be used to create a verbal description of the visual system\]  
2. **Brand name (optional):** Savvy Sloth  
3. **Content theme (optional):** Experimenting and testing AI workflows and automations  
4. **Target audience (optional):** Working professionals who want to learn about and use automations and AI enthusiasts  
5. **Primary platform(s):** Pinterest

#### **Visual System Extraction into Google Sheets (Optional)**

Before moving to image generation, there's one optional, but highly recommended, step. While the image prompts and pin details will drive the automation, storing each visual system in a structured format (Google Sheets for me) is extremely useful for downstream analyses and iterations.

I used the following prompt to extract system data into a Google Sheets-friendly format:

You are a systems analyst.

Your task is to extract structured, automation-ready data from the visual system descriptions provided below.

Do not invent, expand, reinterpret, or improve the systems.  
Your job is to translate them into a format suitable for direct copy-paste into a Google Sheet.

INPUT

You will be given 3 visual system descriptions.

OUTPUT REQUIREMENTS

Produce a table where each row represents one visual system, and each column maps to a reusable system parameter.

Use plain text, not markdown.

Use one row per system, with fields separated by | characters.

The columns must appear in this exact order:

\- system\_id  
\- system\_name  
\- success\_dimensions  
\- design\_intent  
\- colour\_rules  
\- composition\_rules  
\- typography\_style  
\- visual\_style  
\- texture\_rules  
\- prompt\_instruction  
\- prompt\_constraints

RULES

\- Use short, rule-based phrasing (no prose)  
\- Prompt instructions need to be copied exactly without any additional text  
\- Do not include explanations, headers, or commentary  
\- If information is implicit, infer conservatively  
\- Ensure each system is fully usable in isolation

VISUAL SYSTEMS

\[PASTE THE 3 SYSTEM DESCRIPTIONS HERE\]

With more advanced models, you can ask them to generate the table straight away. But with smaller or less advanced models, I found the results to be more reliable if you use plain text \+ delimiter strategy.

Once you copied and pasted the data into Google Sheets, you can separate it into columns by the custom delimiter (‚Äú|‚Äù), and voila:

![A spreadsheet screenshot titled "Visual Systems Testing", showing rows of data with headers including brand name, content theme, target audience, and system ID. The rows contain text entries related to visual and design settings. The toolbar above allows adjustments and formatting options.][image8]

Your exact table schema can look different, depending on what you‚Äôre trying to test, but if you want to follow along, you can copy the following Google Sheet template

#### **System-Driven Image Prompt & Pin Detail Generation**

In the final section, we generate 30 image prompts and corresponding pin details (titles, descriptions, alt text, and tagged topics) for each visual system (90 total).

This system-driven image prompt generator takes one visual system at a time, but I suggest you do all 3 in the same chat for more consistent outputs:

You are a visual content production assistant.

A visual system has already been fully defined.  
You must NOT redesign, reinterpret, or explain the system.

Your job is to EXECUTE it.

INPUT: VISUAL SYSTEM DEFINITION

\[Paste ONE complete visual system here, including Prompt Instruction\]

TASK

Using ONLY the information in the visual system definition:

1\. Treat the Prompt Instruction as the PRIMARY and CONTROLLING RULE.  
2\. Generate final, model-ready AI image prompts that strictly obey:  
    \- Colour Logic  
    \- Composition Rules  
    \- Typography Style (if applicable)  
    \- Visual Style  
    \- Prompt Constraints  
    \- The visual expression of the selected SUCCESS dimensions

You may vary:

\- subject matter  
\- visual metaphor  
\- camera angle or framing  
\- scene context  
\- concrete objects or environments

You must NOT:

\- introduce new aesthetics, moods, or styles  
\- explain or restate the system  
\- reference SUCCESS dimensions by name  
\- include placeholders or variables  
\- include text overlays unless explicitly allowed

OUTPUT REQUIREMENTS

Generate EXACTLY 30 distinct content entries.

Return a table with EXACTLY the following columns:

1\. image\_prompt  
‚Äì a complete, single-paragraph AI image generation prompt  
‚Äì written for direct use with an image model  
‚Äì no placeholders or system explanations

2\. pin\_title  
‚Äì max 100 characters  
‚Äì clear, descriptive, non-clickbait

3\. pin\_description  
‚Äì 2‚Äì3 short sentences  
‚Äì informative, neutral tone  
‚Äì no hashtags

4\. alt\_text  
‚Äì 1‚Äì2 sentences  
‚Äì concise, literal description of what is visible in the image  
‚Äì suitable for accessibility and screen readers

QUALITY BAR

\- Each entry must be visually distinct but system-consistent  
\- Alt text must describe the image itself, not its message  
\- Optimise for clarity, search relevance, and long-term reuse  
\- Assume this content will be generated and published by automation

Begin immediately.  
Do not include commentary or explanations.

To figure out the actual columns I needed to create a pin, I went on Pinterest and tried creating a pin manually. To do so, I needed an image, an image title, an image description, and alt text.

From there, I copied the details into the ‚Äúcontent\_queue‚Äù sheet of my ‚ÄúVisual System Testing \- Pinterest‚Äù spreadsheet:

![A screenshot of a spreadsheet titled "Visual Systems Testing - Pinterest". It shows columns with headers like "content\_id" and "system\_id" and rows of organised data.][image9]

**A quick tip here:** once you've generated the image prompts using one model, try pasting those same prompts into 2-3 other image models (e.g., DALL-E, Midjourney, Nana Banana, or Stable Diffusion) and compare the results. This will help you identify which prompts are model-agnostic versus which ones need tweaking, making your automation more robust to future model changes.
